According to the explicit records in the "Sun Family Genealogy of the Republic of China" compiled in the 21st year of the Republic (1932), Sun Mian from Chanyang Village (now also known as Shenyang Village, under the jurisdiction of Baiyang Township) purchased the land during the fourth year of {{ill|Qiande (Northern Song)|de|Qiande (Northern Song)|ja|乾德 (北宋)|zh|乾德|lt=Qiande|lt_ja=乾德|lt_de=Qiande|lt_zh=乾德|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Qiande (Northern Song)|qq=}} (966 AD) and commenced the construction of Longshou Temple, becoming its first abbot. In the fifth year of {{ill|Tiansheng|de|Tiansheng|ja|天聖|zh|天圣|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tiansheng|qq=}} (1027 AD), a resident of Shangwan Village, {{ill|Lin Deng|de|Lin Deng|ja|林瞪|zh|林瞪|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Lin Deng|qq=}}, converted to Mingjiao at Longshou Temple, later becoming the leading missionary master of Mingjiao in the area and the second abbot of Longshou Temple. His direct disciple, Chen Pingshan, succeeded him.
<ref>{{Cite journal |author=杨富学 |title=林瞪及其在中国摩尼教史上的地位 |journal=中国史研究 |language=zh |publication-place=北京市 |publication-date=2014 |issue=01 |page=109-124 |issn=1002-7963}}</ref>

During the Yuan dynasty, Longshou Temple was renamed Leshan Hall, and during the Ming and Qing dynasties, Leshan Hall underwent two major renovations. In the early years of the People's Republic of China, according to local elders, Leshan Hall still had several courtyards. At the beginning of the [[:en:Cultural Revolution|Cultural Revolution]], Leshan Hall was demolished and subsequently received only simple repairs with makeshift shed-like structures used for storing villagers' farming tools and for temporary shelter from rain. In 2006, Leshan Hall was destroyed by the {{ill|Typhoon Sangmei (2006)|de|Taifun Sangmei (2006)|ja|颱風桑美 (2006年)|zh|颱風桑美|lt=Super Typhoon Sangmei|lt_ja=超強台風桑美|lt_de=Super-Taifun Sangmei|lt_zh=超强台风桑美|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Typhoon Sangmei (2006)|qq=}}, leaving only the foundation columns, steps, and the base of the shrine.
<ref name=":0" />

== Architectural Style and Nature ==
Due to its great antiquity and the lack of written records, the original appearance of Leshan Hall is unknown. The site covers an area of approximately 1560 square meters. Based on photographs of the makeshift structure built at the end of the Cultural Revolution, Leshan Hall relied on columns for support and had no walls on any side. If this construction method was similar to the original, then Leshan Hall would not have been suitable for monastic practice; furthermore, its location at the village entrance, where followers tended to gather, rather than in a secluded area suitable for monks, indicates that Leshan Hall did not possess the typical characteristics of a [[:en:Buddhist temple|Temple]], but rather those of a dining hall. This is one possible reason for the renaming from Longshou Temple to Leshan Hall.
<ref name=":0" />

== Related Activities ==
Every year on the {{ill|Ghost Festival|de|Geisterfest|ja|中元節|zh|中元节|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ghost Festival|qq=}} (the fifteenth day of the seventh month of the {{ill|Lunar Calendar|de|Mondkalender|ja|農暦|zh|农历|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Lunar Calendar|qq=}}), the Manichaean believers of Shangwan Village gather at Leshan Hall to perform a ritual for the transference of the souls of the deceased. This concept of soul transference is at odds with the Manichaean doctrine that venerates light, indicating that Manichaeism in Xiapu, in order to become popular and endure locally, had incorporated some unique elements—such as this soul-transference ritual—that provided comfort to the people.
<ref>{{Cite journal |author=马小鹤 |author2=吴春明 |title=摩尼教与济度亡灵——霞浦明教《奏申牒书科册》研究 |journal=九州学林 |language=zh |publication-date=2010 |issue=03 |page=45-46}}</ref>

