== Name ==
Leshan Hall was originally established as "Longshou Temple" and was renamed "Leshan Hall" during the Yuan dynasty. Initially, the name "Leshan" was believed to be derived from the phrase "The wise delight in water, and the benevolent delight in mountains" found in [[:en:Analects|The Analects]] (Lunyu: Yong Ye). Another theory suggests that the term "Leshan" originates from {{ill|Middle Persian|de|Mittelpersisch|ja|中古ペルシア語|zh|中古波斯语|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Middle Persian|qq=}} {{Lang|pal|Rōšan}} (or {{Lang|pal|Rōšn}}), meaning "light", which corresponds with the Manichaean doctrine that venerates light. Moreover, since the building was more likely used as a dining hall for followers rather than as a monastery (see the "Architectural Style and Nature" section), the change from "Temple" (寺) to "Hall" (堂) was probably due to this reason.
<ref name=":0" />

